00:21:42,619 --> 00:21:43,968
with older women.

514
00:21:44,605 --> 00:21:46,866
- Who's the boy?
- Levi Edwards.

515
00:21:46,894 --> 00:21:49,527
My munitions man. He'll be
inspecting the merchandise.

516
00:21:49,797 --> 00:21:52,401
Why should I make a deal with you, hmm?

517
00:21:52,521 --> 00:21:55,926
Until today, you dismissed
me as a thick-necked sea lion.

518
00:21:55,964 --> 00:21:57,973
I believe I said walrus.

519
00:21:58,093 --> 00:22:00,048
I don't remember, I
was drunk at the time.

520
00:22:00,066 --> 00:22:01,374
TOM: We're here for some guns.

521
00:22:01,560 --> 00:22:03,396
.50 caliber, G3s, as discussed.

522
00:22:03,410 --> 00:22:06,112
- You brought money as discussed?
- The money won't be a problem.

523
00:22:06,131 --> 00:22:07,564
Money's always a problem.

524
00:22:07,566 --> 00:22:09,787
I hear it may be your biggest problem.

525
00:22:11,233 --> 00:22:14,968
Adika, I didn't come here to
waste my time or watch you eat.

526
00:22:15,242 --> 00:22:18,549
You've been trying to get me to
kiss you into the business for years,

527
00:22:18,595 --> 00:22:20,502
I'm here at your table to do just that,

528
00:22:20,539 --> 00:22:22,227
so put down the fork...

529
00:22:22,347 --> 00:22:24,914
♪♪

530
00:22:24,916 --> 00:22:26,418
Where's the money?

531
00:22:27,292 --> 00:22:29,352
I said it won't be a problem.

532
00:22:29,354 --> 00:22:32,422
♪♪

533
00:22:32,603 --> 00:22:34,123
This doesn't feel right.

534
00:22:34,719 --> 00:22:36,040
<i>You</i> don't feel right.

535
00:22:36,160 --> 00:22:38,361
On the contrary, I've never felt better.

536
00:22:38,868 --> 00:22:40,580
Now put away the gun

537
00:22:40,612 --> 00:22:42,910
before you do something you'll regret.

538
00:22:43,714 --> 00:22:45,491
This feels like a setup. No?

539
00:22:45,529 --> 00:22:48,133
GLEN: Okay, okay, I'm
here. I know I'm late.

540
00:22:48,253 --> 00:22:49,929
Traffic was a bitch.

541
00:22:50,366 --> 00:22:55,310
♪♪

542
00:22:55,468 --> 00:22:56,646
Ohh!

543
00:22:57,190 --> 00:22:59,506
Easy! I'm ticklish!

544
00:23:01,516 --> 00:23:02,684
Who the hell is this?

545
00:23:02,804 --> 00:23:05,487
Geynor Collins, TG&L Lending.

546
00:23:05,607 --> 00:23:07,200
I'm the moneyman.

547
00:23:07,251 --> 00:23:09,057
The one who makes the magic happen.

548
00:23:09,433 --> 00:23:11,070
[SNIFFS] Ugh. What are you eating?

549
00:23:11,126 --> 00:23:12,600
Smells like duck.

550
00:23:13,237 --> 00:23:16,932
♪♪

551
00:23:17,279 --> 00:23:21,482
RED: A million reasons for you to
have faith in my financial fortitude.

552
00:23:22,389 --> 00:23:25,101
We'll need the merchandise
delivered by the end of day.

553
00:23:25,119 --> 00:23:26,538
Leave the money.

554
00:23:26,989 --> 00:23:28,338
I will make some calls.

555
00:23:28,556 --> 00:23:32,336
Forgive the overt mistrust, but
I'm not going to hand you a penny

556
00:23:32,373 --> 00:23:35,127
until Mr. Edwards has had a
chance to inspect the shipment.

557
00:23:35,178 --> 00:23:36,546
No deal, then.

558
00:23:36,666 --> 00:23:38,020
I need collateral.

559
00:23:38,022 --> 00:23:41,623
♪♪

560
00:23:42,053 --> 00:23:43,481
Then take Edwards.

561
00:23:43,956 --> 00:23:46,821
If there's a bump in the
road, do with him as you wish.

562
00:23:46,881 --> 00:23:48,649
Now get your merchandise in order.

563
00:23:48,667 --> 00:23:51,257
I'll call you with a
rendezvous site shortly.

564
00:23:53,582 --> 00:23:55,043
We can make this work.

565
00:23:55,163 --> 00:23:56,685
I'll take your word for it.

566
00:23:56,754 --> 00:23:57,824
Take him.

567
00:23:58,145 --> 00:23:59,775
♪♪

568
00:24:00,206 --> 00:24:01,210
Really?

569
00:24:01,513 --> 00:24:05,676
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

570
00:24:05,876 --> 00:24:07,649
♪♪

571
00:24:09,244 --> 00:24:12,407
SMOKEY: Yes. I... I'm on
my way... 45 minutes tops.

572
00:24:12,440 --> 00:24:15,567
Smokey, Buhari's plane is supposed
to land here in four hours.

573
00:24:15,579 --> 00:24:17,904
If I were throwing a
picnic, it'd be lovely,

574
00:24:17,939 --> 00:24:20,688
- but there are trees.
- The runway will be ready.

575
00:24:20,723 --> 00:24:23,270
Tell that wizard the
McClintock boys are here!

576
00:24:23,293 --> 00:24:26,002
Where the hell is he? We need
the shovels and chainsaws!

577
00:24:26,020 --> 00:24:28,903
- Shovels and chainsaws.
- Tell her to button her lip. I...

578
00:24:28,921 --> 00:24:31,077
I... I got shovels and chainsaws.

579
00:24:31,106 --> 00:24:33,537
- Smokey, if this doesn't work...
- Mr. Reddington,

580
00:24:33,549 --> 00:24:35,087
I need you to trust me on this.

581
00:24:35,089 --> 00:24:37,467
We are going to belly
that gunrunner's plane

582
00:24:37,485 --> 00:24:39,171
in that field, so help me God,

583
00:24:39,195 --> 00:24:42,218
I just need 45 minutes to
get Leroy and Quackers there.

584
00:24:42,258 --> 00:24:44,107
We'll jive then, my friend.

585
00:24:44,787 --> 00:24:47,217
Who the hell are Leroy and Quackers?

586
00:24:47,252 --> 00:24:49,275
ARAM: Based on the insurance records,

587
00:24:49,293 --> 00:24:51,758
I think maybe I figured
out who the next target is.

588
00:24:51,799 --> 00:24:55,103
- LIZ: Insurance records?
- Waterday's in the insurance business, too?

589
00:24:55,135 --> 00:24:57,456
Oh, no, but they take out a ton of it.

590
00:24:57,470 --> 00:24:59,213
Life-insurance policies on the lives

591
00:24:59,214 --> 00:25:01,009
of the people whose
settlements they buy.

592
00:25:01,027 --> 00:25:04,125
Johnson said the company
paid Stansbury $100,000,

593
00:25:04,162 --> 00:25:06,664
but they had only received $62,000

594
00:25:06,688 --> 00:25:08,888
when Stansbury died and the
settlement payment stopped.

595
00:25:08,902 --> 00:25:10,730
That's true, Waterday
lost a few thousand

596
00:25:10,753 --> 00:25:12,423
on the settlement payouts, but

597
00:25:12,465 --> 00:25:16,487
they took out a $5 million
policy on Stansbury's life.

598
00:25:16,488 --> 00:25:19,502
So when he died, they made a fortune.

599
00:25:19,535 --> 00:25:22,172
Let me guess... they had policies
on the other victims, too.

600
00:25:22,200 --> 00:25:25,014
- Isn't that a little obvious?
- Uh, yes and no.

601
00:25:25,084 --> 00:25:27,677
First, Waterday had
policies on all of the people

602
00:25:27,693 --> 00:25:30,008
whose structured settlements
they bought, not just the victims.

603
00:25:30,042 --> 00:25:31,624
And second... the victims.

604
00:25:31,642 --> 00:25:35,709
It looks like they pick ones who
are living on "borrowed time."

605
00:25:35,744 --> 00:25:39,003
Cancer victims, addicts, people
whose illnesses may explain

606
00:25:39,004 --> 00:25:41,887
the type of erratic
behavior that could result

607
00:25:41,907 --> 00:25:44,998
- in a deadly altercation with the police.
- LIZ: And the next target...

608
00:25:45,010 --> 00:25:46,343
you said you might know who that is.

609
00:25:46,463 --> 00:25:48,779
Yes. Based on the three knowns...

610
00:25:48,790 --> 00:25:50,213
the recipient of a
structured settlement,

611
00:25:50,215 --> 00:25:51,915
a preexisting medical condition,

612
00:25:51,917 --> 00:25:54,551
and a large insurance
policy on their life...

613
00:25:54,553 --> 00:25:57,654
I found one name in
the Waterday database...

614
00:25:57,675 --> 00:25:59,243
Robert Urwiller.

615
00:25:59,658 --> 00:26:03,593
♪♪

616
00:26:03,713 --> 00:26:05,619
Let me get two of them scratchers.

617
00:26:06,452 --> 00:26:07,992
Might be my lucky day.

618
00:26:08,167 --> 00:26:11,462
♪♪

619
00:26:12,146 --> 00:26:16,072
[ELEPHANT TRUMPETS]

620
00:26:16,518 --> 00:26:20,169
SMOKEY: Let's get that last
maple to the south pulled!

621
00:26:20,188 --> 00:26:21,908
That oak, too!

622
00:26:21,931 --> 00:26:25,811
Mikey and John, run a string line
and mow me some threshold markings.

623
00:26:25,834 --> 00:26:30,211
Humberto, check our compaction
in the touchdown zone!

624
00:26:30,223 --> 00:26:34,072
Chip-chop! Chip-chop-chip,
folks! Show time in 20!

625
00:26:34,287 --> 00:26:36,624
[CHUCKLES] My land!

626
00:26:36,744 --> 00:26:39,066
They don't make men like
that anymore, do they?

627
00:26:39,083 --> 00:26:40,775
Thank the Lord.

628
00:26:41,025 --> 00:26:44,000
♪♪

629
00:26:44,653 --> 00:26:46,508
[CELLPHONE RINGING]

630
00:26:46,932 --> 00:26:51,775
♪♪

631
00:26:57,282 --> 00:26:59,082
[ENGINE STARTS]

632
00:26:59,084 --> 00:27:04,688
♪♪

633
00:27:10,861 --> 00:27:12,674
- That's it, huh?
- Yep.

634
00:27:12,710 --> 00:27:16,501
- Was it brought in like that?
- No idea. Sign here.

635
00:27:18,467 --> 00:27:19,949
Thanks.

636
00:27:31,062 --> 00:27:32,425
[CLANGING]

637
00:27:32,611 --> 00:27:35,047
[CELLPHONE RINGING, BEEPS]

638
00:27:36,058 --> 00:27:38,180
Ressler. Whatever
you're doing has to wait.

639
00:27:38,233 --> 00:27:40,181
Sir. This situation has been handled.

640
00:27:40,193 --> 00:27:43,349
Good, because we got a location
on the blacklister's next target.

641
00:27:43,646 --> 00:27:46,575
♪♪

642
00:27:47,025 --> 00:27:48,374
Ressler?

643
00:27:48,589 --> 00:27:51,251
- Ressler, you there?
- I'm on my way.

644
00:27:51,548 --> 00:27:53,507
♪♪

645
00:27:53,809 --> 00:27:56,379
RED: Smokey, you were
born a century too late.

646
00:27:56,408 --> 00:27:59,478
You're a miracle worker.
Heddie, I can't thank you enough

647
00:27:59,489 --> 00:28:02,007
- for keeping us on budget.
- Oh, you had not budget.

648
00:28:02,042 --> 00:28:03,670
- Well, there you are.
- [CHUCKLES]

649
00:28:03,838 --> 00:28:05,285
[ENGINE STARTS]

650
00:28:05,692 --> 00:28:08,664
[MARC SCIBILIA'S "MY
TIME IS COMIN'" PLAYS]

651
00:28:08,666 --> 00:28:13,065
♪♪

652
00:28:13,971 --> 00:28:16,672
[JET ENGINES WHIRS]

653
00:28:17,517 --> 00:28:19,854
♪ I've been waitin' ♪

654
00:28:19,974 --> 00:28:22,418
- ♪ for the longest time ♪
- It's him.

655
00:28:22,476 --> 00:28:23,898
This ought to be interesting.

656
00:28:23,962 --> 00:28:27,783
Agent Keen, I've got Urwiller's
car heading east on Irving Street.

657
00:28:27,785 --> 00:28:29,269
Do you have a vehicle description?

658
00:28:29,287 --> 00:28:32,310
You are looking for a
1994 tan Toyota Tercel...

659
00:28:32,368 --> 00:28:35,166
- which just made a left on Georgia.
- You still can't get him on his cell?

660
00:28:35,189 --> 00:28:37,801
- I tried at least a dozen times...
- Trying again now.

661
00:28:38,677 --> 00:28:40,137
[CELLPHONE RINGING]

662
00:28:40,257 --> 00:28:44,607
- ♪ Can't nobody save me ♪
- [SIREN CHIRPS]

663
00:28:44,852 --> 00:28:46,610
[RINGING CONTINUES]

664
00:28:46,612 --> 00:28:50,677
♪♪

665
00:28:51,643 --> 00:28:59,171
♪ Devil, please
don't take me alive ♪

666
00:28:59,291 --> 00:29:01,759
♪♪

667
00:29:01,991 --> 00:29:03,741
♪ Ah, ooh ♪

668
00:29:03,782 --> 00:29:05,776
Mr. Cooper, I just
spoke with Agent Ressler

669
00:29:05,788 --> 00:29:08,636
and gave him Agent Keen's
10-20. He's en route as we speak.

670
00:29:08,696 --> 00:29:11,830
- And Urwiller? You make contact?
- Uh, not yet, but we're still trying.

671
00:29:11,853 --> 00:29:13,399
♪ Coming ♪

672
00:29:13,725 --> 00:29:15,406
♪ Ah, ooh, yeah ♪

673
00:29:15,408 --> 00:29:20,177
- [CELLPHONE RINGING]
- ♪ Ah, ooh, yeah ♪

674
00:29:20,179 --> 00:29:24,401
- ♪ My time is coming, coming ♪
- [RINGING CONTINUES]

675
00:29:24,521 --> 00:29:27,372
On my damn cellphone. Sorry.

676
00:29:27,492 --> 00:29:30,220
- ♪ My time is coming, coming soon ♪
- License and registration, please.

677
00:29:30,694 --> 00:29:33,680
- I'm sorry...
- License and registration.

678
00:29:33,847 --> 00:29:36,619
♪♪

679
00:29:37,856 --> 00:29:40,382
Aram, we have eyes. There's
a unit on scene now...

680
00:29:40,400 --> 00:29:42,771
notify Annapolis Police and
get cars there right away.

681
00:29:42,772 --> 00:29:43,775
Copy that.

682
00:29:43,856 --> 00:29:46,417
- Whoa! What are you doing?!
- [SIREN WAILING]

683
00:29:47,283 --> 00:29:49,475
♪ Ah, ooh, yeah ♪

684
00:29:50,045 --> 00:29:52,260
- ♪ Ah, ooh, yeah ♪
- LIZ: FBI!

685
00:29:52,429 --> 00:29:53,766
Drop your weapon!

686
00:29:53,815 --> 00:29:56,039
Put the gun down. I'm
not gonna warn you again.

687
00:29:56,080 --> 00:29:59,853
♪ My time is coming, coming ♪

688
00:30:00,155 --> 00:30:06,398
♪ My time is coming, coming soon ♪

689
00:30:07,090 --> 00:30:09,432
RED: Adika! How was your flight in?

690
00:30:09,460 --> 00:30:11,525
ADIKA: Bumpy as hell. Are
you trying to kill us all?

691
00:30:11,580 --> 00:30:14,454
Well, I picked the site
for its magnificent views.

692
00:30:14,463 --> 00:30:17,580
- Levi, you look well.
- Any chance we can untie me?

693
00:30:18,524 --> 00:30:20,900
Adika, I appreciate the good faith.

694
00:30:20,910 --> 00:30:23,426
And if your merchandise
is as good as I hear,

695
00:30:23,486 --> 00:30:25,876
there's no end to
what you and I could...

696
00:30:26,337 --> 00:30:27,611
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

697
00:30:27,919 --> 00:30:29,580
- What is it?
- Shh.

698
00:30:29,582 --> 00:30:32,650
[BIRD CHIRPING]

699
00:30:32,956 --> 00:30:35,082
You hear that? There it is again.

700
00:30:37,236 --> 00:30:38,761
I don't hear anything.

701
00:30:39,225 --> 00:30:40,724
[BIRD CHIRPING]

702
00:30:40,844 --> 00:30:42,393
A piping plover.

703
00:30:42,868 --> 00:30:46,003
Their breeding grounds
are along coastal beaches

704
00:30:46,031 --> 00:30:48,905
and alkali marshes, so...

705
00:30:49,175 --> 00:30:52,175
to hear that bell-like call

706
00:30:52,189 --> 00:30:54,403
from a shorebird this far inland...

707
00:30:54,523 --> 00:30:57,650
my gosh, poor little fella must be lost.

708
00:30:57,682 --> 00:30:59,455
Do you want to talk birds or guns?

709
00:30:59,524 --> 00:31:02,680
- [PLOVER CHIRPING]
- [GUNFIRE]

710
00:31:03,101 --> 00:31:05,282
- [CHIRPING STOPS]
- Impressive.

711
00:31:05,776 --> 00:31:07,855
Not if you're a lonely little plover.

712
00:31:07,975 --> 00:31:09,553
The other five crates are in the jet.

713
00:31:09,753 --> 00:31:11,799
.50 caliber and 3Gs, as discussed.

714
00:31:11,832 --> 00:31:14,665
Dembe, if you could please
grab Mr. Buhari's payment.

715
00:31:14,721 --> 00:31:16,121
Levi, you look fit.

716
00:31:16,321 --> 00:31:18,929
You can help me load the merchandise.

717
00:31:19,563 --> 00:31:21,828
[SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE]

718
00:31:22,019 --> 00:31:24,735
♪♪

719
00:31:25,251 --> 00:31:27,032
Adika, what the hell have you done?

720
00:31:27,083 --> 00:31:29,418
- ATF!
- Everybody on the ground!

721
00:31:29,492 --> 00:31:31,422
- ATF! Get on the ground!
- Let me see your hands!

722
00:31:31,464 --> 00:31:34,088
I said hands! Get on the ground now!

723
00:31:34,679 --> 00:31:36,139
I said don't move!

724
00:31:36,344 --> 00:31:38,214
- Nice work, Chief.
- Hands!

725
00:31:38,451 --> 00:31:40,751
♪♪

726
00:31:40,753 --> 00:31:43,821
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

727
00:31:46,592 --> 00:31:48,926
[POLICE RADIO CHATTER]

728
00:31:55,336 --> 00:31:56,833
Nice ride.

729
00:31:57,475 --> 00:31:59,522
Guy I was helping
out... it belongs to him.

730
00:31:59,555 --> 00:32:01,750
Okay. Why are you driving it?

731
00:32:01,797 --> 00:32:04,606
Turns out he killed a guy,
stuck him in the trunk.

732
00:32:04,658 --> 00:32:06,244
I'm dumping the body for him.

733
00:32:06,449 --> 00:32:08,067
Officer Serry won't talk.

734
00:32:08,235 --> 00:32:10,793
Aram told me that the
Waterday CEO is dead.

735
00:32:10,825 --> 00:32:12,727
But, more than likely,
he had an accomplice.

736
00:32:12,788 --> 00:32:14,881
And, for all we know,
is soliciting more cops.

737
00:32:14,932 --> 00:32:17,725
If we can get to Serry, we might
be able to put an end to this.

738
00:32:17,781 --> 00:32:19,158
Mind if I take a run at her?

739
00:32:19,278 --> 00:32:21,822
Why not... one crooked cop to the next?

740
00:32:21,846 --> 00:32:23,975
Maybe you can bond over
the body in your trunk.

741
00:32:24,012 --> 00:32:25,607
There's a body in the trunk?

742
00:32:25,617 --> 00:32:27,131
Hurry up before it gets ripe!

743
00:32:27,514 --> 00:32:31,194
I told her I wanted a lawyer.
I'm not answering any questions.

744
00:32:34,421 --> 00:32:35,928
A Mongolian peasant

745
00:32:36,467 --> 00:32:39,649
gets brought into an office,
where an important man offers him

746
00:32:39,660 --> 00:32:41,779
a million dollars on one condition...

747
00:32:42,100 --> 00:32:44,620
that he press the red
button on his desk.

748
00:32:45,350 --> 00:32:46,987
And he tells the poor man that

749
00:32:47,107 --> 00:32:48,447
if he presses the button,

750
00:32:48,494 --> 00:32:51,089
an old man in Mongolia drops dead.

751
00:32:51,503 --> 00:32:53,242
Now, he won't tell him why, only that

752
00:32:53,321 --> 00:32:55,209
his death is good for the people.

753
00:32:55,474 --> 00:32:57,809
So he pushes the button,

754
00:32:57,842 --> 00:32:59,646
takes the money, and goes home.

755
00:33:00,208 --> 00:33:01,765
But he's haunted by what he did.

756
00:33:01,971 --> 00:33:04,426
He can't spend any of
the money, and eventually,

757
00:33:04,757 --> 00:33:06,422
he commits suicide.

758
00:33:07,264 --> 00:33:09,344
A man recently told me that story.

759
00:33:09,381 --> 00:33:12,306
Said we all have a Mongolian
peasant in our lives...

760
00:33:12,426 --> 00:33:14,763
something we've done
that we're ashamed of...

